HEADWORD: Furl
<hw>Furl</hw> <pr>(f⟦ucir⟧rl)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Furled</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ucir⟧rld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Furling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Contr. fr.
<ets>furdle</ets>, fr. <ets>fardel</ets> bundle: cf. F.
<ets>ferler</ets> to furl, OF. <ets>fardeler</ets> to pack. See
<er>Furdle</er>, <er>Fardel</er>, and cf. <er>Farl</er>.]</ety> <def>To
draw up or gather into close compass; to wrap or roll, as a sail, close
to the yard, stay, or mast, or, as a flag, close to or around its staff,
securing it there by a gasket or line.</def> <au>Totten.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>furled</ent>⟦br⟧
